A. Visually compare annual salamander counts in old growth (OG) and clear cut (CC) sections of Mack Creek

Figure 3: Annual Salamander Counts in Old Growth (OG) & Clear Cut (CC) Forests along Mack Creek. Counts of Pacific Giant Salamander in clear cut forest and old growth forest sections along Mack Creek are shown from 1993 through 2017. Data [Gregory S.V. 2016](https://doi.org/10.6073/pasta/5de64af9c11579266ef20da2ff32f702]

Observations of Pacific Giant Salamanders along Mack Creek are compared between the old growth sections and clear cut sections between the years of 1993 and 2017. As shown in Figure 3, the overall graph shapes and counts are very similar between the two different sections between the years. General trends along both graphs show that there was an increase in observation counts during the year 2002. There was a decrease in counts during 2014 and then the counts then increased again after that. These trends are consistent across both creek sections, indicating that there may not be a difference in Pacific Giant Salamanders ability to survive in the two different habitat types.

  1. Is there a significant difference in where in the channel Pacific giant salamanders are located (pool, cascade or side channel) between the two sections (old growth and clear cut)?

Using the 2017 Pacific Giant Salamander counts in clear cut sections (Cascades: 247 (67.1%), Pool: 31 (8.4%), Side Channel: 90 (24.5%)) and old growth sections (Cascades: 201 (62.8%), Pool: 45 (14.1%), Side Channel: 74 (23.1%)) in Mack Creek, there is no association (0.0626222) between Pacific Giant Salamander counts in clear cut and old growth sections. In other words, there is not a significant effect of forest condition on where in the channel Pacific Giant Salamanders are found.

H0: Is there a significant difference in where pacific giant salamanders are located between the two sections?

HA: There is no significant difference.

D. Compare weights of Pacific giant salamanders in clear cut and old growth forest sections of the creek in 2017

section mean_weight sd_weight sample_size
Clear cut 7.775870 9.904738 368
Old growth 6.583333 8.955275 328

Is there a significant difference in mean weights for Pacific giant salamanders observed in the two forest sections (clear cut and old growth) in 2017?

There is NO significant difference in mean weights for Pacific Giant Salamanders between the two forest sections (clear cut & old growth) in 2017. The mean salamander weights for clear cut, 7.78 grams, and old growth, 6.58 grams, forest sections do not differ significantly (two-sided t-test, t(693) = 1.67 p = 0.096) and the effect size is small (Cohens D = 0.13). This indicates that between the two forest sections, mean Pacific Giant Salamander weight differences are not significant nor substantive.
